latestPosts.caption:
Tallin, the picturesque capital of Estonia looks something that is straight out of a fairy tale! The cobbled stone Old Town spills of medieval streets and spires. Tallin is beautiful, breathtaking and bustling with vibrant cafés with the most delicious vegan food! 

We took a short cruise 🚢 from Helsinki to arrive at Tallin, crossing the stunning Baltic Sea 🌊

You know how people say clothes can give you confidence?
For me, it’s always been Indian block prints, rather Indian wear. Every single time. I stand straighter, feel sharper, smile wider. It’s like my body remembers who I am when I wear it.

Since the beginning-literally, since memory began-Indian wear in our house meant block prints. Handloom. Soft muls. Earthy colours. That slightly faded indigo. That smell of natural dyes and something old school. That was us. And it always felt like me.

I’ve always gravitated to it, much to the chagrin of many who’d roll their eyes and say, “Ugh, you look like one of those pseudo-intellectuals… you know, the ones who hung around Prithvi before the Gen Zs moved in.”
And I’d smile. Because block prints, silver jewellery, and bindis have been my first love. And honestly, I still think there’s nothing cooler.

What I didn’t know back then was that this love would one day become a living, breathing part of my life. That what I wore because I loved it would turn into something I’d build my life around.

I believe in serendipity, like very strongly. In the quiet magic of things falling into place without making a fuss about it. In how people, places, choices… somehow they’re all connected. Not always immediately, but eventually. In ways you don’t always see but somehow feel.

So here’s to that.
Here’s to more of the things I love this year-more block prints, more silver, more bindis.
And more time spent doing what makes my heart feel at home.

latestPosts.caption:
People maketh a place, not the building, chicca.
Not the skyline, not the shiny cafés.
The ones who make you feel like you belong, even when you don’t speak the language.

Seoul wasn’t in the views.
It was in the vendors. The strangers. The everyday humdrum.
It’s never just the place. But it’s always the people.
These are our favorite moments, framed not by architecture, but by people.

Seoul didn’t move us because it was pretty.
It moved us because it was present.
Because strangers felt familiar.
Because the city didn’t try to impress,
it just quietly let us in.

Must visit places / Things to see in Seoul, South Korea.

1 Gwangjang Market
2 Namdaemun Market
3 Myeongdong Night Market
4 Seongsu-dong
5 Ikseon-dong Hanok Village
6 Cheonggyecheon Stream
7 Gangnam District
8 Convenience Stores - Nice to c u, K Mart, 7Eleven, GS25

latestPosts.caption:
Think: a sprawling café, effortlessly stunning, overlooking an endless field. A chilled iced latte in one hand, a book in the other.Need we more?

People say Jeju is gorgeous.
That’s it.
That’s it?

Have we become so overstimulated by cities? So used to noise, chaos, and a constant need for more that something as simple as beauty doesn’t feel like enough anymore?

But Jeju is enough.
I’ve come to realise I just need air that smells like rain, grass swaying in slow motion, and a sense of stillness that feels almost rare.
Jeju gave me all of that. And more.
It was just… perfectly enough.

And right in the middle of this quiet beauty is Jejudang Bakery-a café so vast it could be mistaken for a museum. Double-height ceilings. Indoor greenery. A full-sized tractor parked between wooden tables. And views that make you sit longer than you intended, without meaning to scroll or speak.

If you can’t do slow, Jeju isn’t for you.
There’s no nightlife. No long list of things to tick off.
You don’t come here to be entertained. You come to feel something slower. Softer.

And maybe realise, in the most unexpected way, that just gorgeous might actually be everything.
